english:
  title: Preface to the Eight Masters of Tang and Song Poetry Selection
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven and earth open and close; the transformations of nature are boundless. The sun, moon, and stars possess the natural patterns of form; thunder, wind, and rain possess the natural patterns of sound. Among these, man emerges as the most spiritual of all beings. Benevolence, righteousness, propriety, and wisdom are the foundations of literary form; joy, anger, sorrow, and pleasure are the stirrings of emotion. What emanates from emotion takes shape in literary form—thus are born the rhythmic and measured compositions that arise from sighs and earnest utterances. Such were the songs exchanged in the court of the ancient Yu dynasty and the verses composed by the five brothers: all sprung from nature itself, becoming the very source of the National Songs and the Elegies. Therefore, one cannot compose poetry without understanding the spirit of these National Songs and Elegies.

    Yet the orthodox and variant forms of poetry have also risen and fallen with the ages. Thus the two southern states, the Elegies and Hymns could not remain unchanged. They transformed once into the Songs of Chu; transformed again into the verse of Han and Wei. By the time of the Eastern regions, though claiming proximity to antiquity, they abandoned all law and measure. Each poet established his own style, vying in ornate beauty and strange invention, pursuing only abandon and excess. Obscure abstractions dazzled with their own emptiness, flowing into boundless diffusion without shore. The residual meaning of the Six Methods faded away; the lingering echoes of the Four Beginnings fell silent.

    Alas! Yet the human heart and heavenly principle have never been extinguished. The instructive words of Fu Shuo still appear in Zhuge Liang's memorial; the discourse on benevolence and righteousness from Mencius still manifests in Lu Xuan's memorials. Does not this refute what Shao Zi claimed—that after the Sage's selection of the Odes, no poetry existed?

    When the Li clan rose to establish Tang and the Zhao clan brought forth Song, Li Bai, Du Fu, Wei Yingwu, and Liu Zongyuan sang out before; Ouyang Xiu, Wang Anshi, Su Shi, and Huang Tingjian continued after. They read only the words of sages and scorned the music of Zheng and Wei. Pursuing Qu Yuan and Song Yu, denouncing Yang Xiong and Sima Xiangru—this is why Li Bai became sage of poetry. Ascending to the righteousness of the National Songs while gathering the strengths of countless masters, his breast swallowing the vast marshes while his breath dammed the Yellow River—thus Du Fu achieved the synthesis of all.

    Du Fu's precision and beauty, his boldness and freedom from constraint—such is the poetry of the Western master. Ouyang Xiu's delicate mystery, his graceful clarity, his gentle words and profound feeling—such is the poetry of the Lingnan master. Wang Anshi draws purely from his own breast without artifice; Su Shi employs lofty conception with exacting measure; Su Che's words transcend all convention, washing clean ten thousand ages; Huang Tingjian's crystalline novelty and ingenious craft shine like pearls at hand. All have restored the severed thread of the Six Methods and reconnected the lingering echoes of the Four Beginnings. Truly, this is a renaissance of the poetic way, and one may still perceive in our time such beautiful acclaim and supreme wonder. What path remains for those devoted to poetry but this?

    I, dwelling in leisure without duties, have entertained myself with the study of poetry. My mind and eye have lingered so long among these eight masters, forgetting weariness as the hours pass, that years have accumulated thus. The ancients said: "In seeking poetry, cherish simplicity; do not pursue the tortuous and forced." This is surely the subtle secret of selecting poetry. Moreover, those who came before in selecting poetry universally gathered works from many hands, compiling them into small volumes. Though they captured the ingenious methods of diverse masters, they could not escape the faults of fragmentation and disorder. Now it is otherwise. I have taken only from these eight masters' collected works what is easy for people to understand and convenient for perusal, organized them by three poetic forms, and divided them into ten volumes, naming this work *The Tang and Song Eight Masters Poetry Selection*. I share this humbly with a few like-minded companions. Those who regard this selection, if they embody it with the rectitude of their true nature and employ it to harmonize their words and conduct, shall gradually perceive that beneath the indulgence and ease lies the gentle, sincere, and generous spirit of antiquity. Surely this is more than merely reciting wind and moon!
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The ''Six Methods'' (六義) refer to the classical categories of poetic expression: Wind (風), Elegance (雅), Hymn (頌), Exposition (賦), Comparison (比), and Evocation (興).'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The ''Four Beginnings'' (四始) refer to the four initial types of poetry in the Classic of Poetry: the National Songs of Zhou South, Shao South, the Major Elegance, and the Minor Elegance.'
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three poetic forms' (三體法) likely refers to the classification of Tang and Song poetry into regulated verse (律詩), ancient-style verse (古詩), and other forms.
